{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "A new home in Seoul honors tradition while keeping up with the times.", "abstract": "Art historian Hongnam Kim's multi-level home in Seoul, Korea, combines the design of a traditional Korean wooden structure, called the hanok, with a modern basement and workspace. Photos (M)", "section_name": null, "print_page": "5", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Elaine", "role": "reported", "lastname": "LOUIE", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By ELAINE LOUIE"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/greathomesanddestinations/a-modern-home-in-seoul-honors-tradition.html", "lead_paragraph": "Seoul, South Korea A few years ago, when Hongnam Kim, a professor here at Ewha Womans University, decided to build a house, she knew she wanted it to take the form of a hanok, the traditional wooden structure dating back to the Joseon dynasty in 1392. But she also needed a modern basement where she could pursue her work.", "headline": {"main": "Connecting the Centuries", "kicker": "ON LOCATION"}, "_id": "4fd2a9988eb7c8105d894fc9", "word_count": 691, "multimedia": [{"height": 75, "url": "images/2012/05/03/garden/03LOCATION_SPAN/03LOCATION_SPAN-thumbStandard.jpg", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "images/2012/05/03/garden/03LOCATION_SPAN/03LOCATION_SPAN-thumbStandard.jpg", "hasthumbnail": "Y", "thumbnailwidth": 75, "thumbnailheight": 75}, "subtype": "thumbnail", "width": 75, "type": "image"}, {"height": 360, "url": "images/2012/05/03/garden/03LOCATION_SPAN/03LOCATION_SPAN-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2012/05/03/garden/03LOCATION_SPAN/03LOCATION_SPAN-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": 600, "xlargeheight": 360, "hasxlarge": "Y"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}], "pub_date": "2012-05-02T00:00:00Z", "source": "The New York Times", "news_desk": "Great Homes and Destinations", "keywords": [{"name": "persons", "value": "HONGNAM KIM"}, {"name": "glocations", "value": "SEOUL (SOUTH K